<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,298]" pageId="12" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,264,151,177]" pageId="12" pageNumber="39">Note.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Dietrich &amp; Dmitriev" authorityYear="2006" box="[567,758,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neozygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadricornis">
<emphasis box="[567,758,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="39">N. quadricornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich &amp; Dmitriev" authorityYear="2007" box="[824,951,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neozygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sordida">
<emphasis box="[824,951,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="39">N. sordida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a similarly bifurcated dorsal pygofer appendage, but differs in its smaller size, paler coloration, and in the structure of the aedeagus, which has the gonoduct extended diagonally across the shaft rather than parallel to the posterior margin. This species is named in memory of Emilano Zapata Salazar (1879–1919), hero of the Mexican Revolution.
</paragraph>
